// # Biblical Foundation
//
// Scripture: "A false balance is abomination to the LORD: but a just weight
// is his delight." - Proverbs 11:1
//
// Principle: Integrity verification - ensuring dependencies are exactly what
// they claim to be, untampered and trustworthy.
//
// Anchor: "Providing for honest things, not only in the sight of the Lord,
// but also in the sight of men." - 2 Corinthians 8:21
//
// # CPI-SI Identity
//
// Component Type: Rails (security infrastructure)
//
// Role: Cryptographic verification of dependency integrity
//
// Paradigm: CPI-SI framework component - trust verification
//
// # Purpose & Function
//
// Purpose: Ensure reproducible builds with verified dependencies
//
// Core Design: Cryptographic checksums (SHA-256) for all dependency content
//
// Key Features:
//
//   - Verifies dependencies haven't been modified since download
//   - Enables reproducible builds across machines
//   - Detects supply chain attacks (modified packages)
//   - Tracks checksums for both module content and go.mod files
//
// # Why This Matters
//
// Security: Without go.sum, a compromised proxy could serve malicious code
// that appears to be a legitimate dependency.
//
// Reproducibility: go.sum ensures everyone building the project gets the
// exact same dependency versions with identical content.
//
// Trust: The checksum file is the cryptographic proof that dependencies
// are what they claim to be.
//
