//
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Checksum Verification
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Verify checksums are correct:
//
//   go mod verify       # Verify all downloaded modules match checksums
//   go mod download     # Download and verify all dependencies
//
// Output: "all modules verified" means checksums match downloaded content.
//
// Common Issues:
//
//   "checksum mismatch" - Dependency content differs from expected.
//     Cause: Corrupted download, tampered package, or proxy issue.
//     Fix: Delete go.sum entry and re-download, or investigate tampering.
//
//   "missing go.sum entry" - Dependency not yet checksummed.
//     Fix: Run 'go mod tidy' to add missing entries.
//
//   "SECURITY ERROR" from GOPROXY - Module content doesn't match checksum.
//     CRITICAL: Do not ignore. Investigate potential supply chain attack.
//
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Modification Policy
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// NEVER Modify go.sum Manually:
//   ❌ Don't add checksum lines by hand
//   ❌ Don't edit existing checksums
//   ❌ Don't delete checksums to "fix" issues
//
// Let Go Tooling Manage:
//   ✅ 'go mod tidy' - Add/remove checksums as needed
//   ✅ 'go get' - Add checksums for new dependencies
//   ✅ 'go mod download' - Populate checksums for all dependencies
//
// When to Regenerate:
//   - After resolving merge conflicts in go.sum
//   - After git reset/revert of go.sum
//   - After "checksum mismatch" investigation
//
// Regeneration:
//   rm go.sum                   # Remove corrupted file
//   go mod download             # Regenerate from go.mod
//   go mod verify               # Verify new checksums
//
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Version Control Guidelines
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// ALWAYS Commit go.sum:
//   - Ensures reproducible builds for all developers
//   - CI/CD uses committed checksums for verification
//   - Documents exact dependency versions used
//
// Merge Conflicts:
//   1. Accept either version (or combine both)
//   2. Run 'go mod tidy' to reconcile
//   3. Run 'go mod verify' to validate
//   4. Commit resolved go.sum
//
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Security Considerations
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// go.sum is a Security Control:
//   - First line of defense against supply chain attacks
//   - Verifies module content matches original author's release
//   - Protects against compromised proxies or mirrors
//
// Go Checksum Database (sum.golang.org):
//   - Public database of module checksums
//   - Go verifies against this database by default
//   - GOSUMDB environment variable controls this
//
// Private Modules:
//   - Use GOPRIVATE for modules not in public database
//   - go.sum still provides verification within your organization
//   - Example: GOPRIVATE=github.com/yourorg/*
//
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Related Files
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// go.mod: Declares dependencies (what to download)
// go.sum: Verifies dependencies (are they authentic)
// go.work.sum: Workspace-level checksums (if using go.work)
// vendor/: Vendored dependencies (if using 'go mod vendor')
//
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Closing Note
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// go.sum is the cryptographic guarantee of build integrity.
